member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.CohortStudy
member.summary: Also known as a panel study. A cohort study is a form of longitudinal study used in medicine and social science. It is one type of study design and should be compared with a cross-sectional study. A cohort is a group of people who share a common characteristic or experience within a defined period (e.g., are born, leave school, lose their job, are exposed to a drug or a vaccine, etc.). The comparison group may be the general population from which the cohort is drawn, or it may be another cohort of persons thought to have had little or no exposure to the substance under investigation, but otherwise similar. Alternatively, subgroups within the cohort may be compared with each other.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCause
member.summary: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.DifferentialDiagnosis
member.summary: One of a set of differential diagnoses for the condition. Specifically, a closely-related or competing diagnosis typically considered later in the cognitive process whereby this medical condition is distinguished from others most likely responsible for a similar collection of signs and symptoms to reach the most parsimonious diagnosis or diagnoses in a patient.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Epidemiology
member.summary: The characteristics of associated patients, such as age, gender, race etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.ExpectedPrognosis
member.summary: The likely outcome in either the short term or long term of the medical condition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.NaturalProgression
member.summary: The expected progression of the condition if it is not treated and allowed to progress naturally.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Pathophysiology
member.summary: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.PossibleComplication
member.summary: A possible unexpected and unfavorable evolution of a medical condition. Complications may include worsening of the signs or symptoms of the disease, extension of the condition to other organ systems, etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.PossibleTreatment
member.summary: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.PrimaryPrevention
member.summary: A preventative therapy used to prevent an initial occurrence of the medical condition, such as vaccination.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.RiskFactor
member.summary: A modifiable or non-modifiable factor that increases the risk of a patient contracting this condition, e.g. age, coexisting condition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.SecondaryPrevention
member.summary: A preventative therapy used to prevent reoccurrence of the medical condition after an initial episode of the condition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.SignOrSymptom
member.summary: A sign or symptom of this condition. Signs are objective or physically observable manifestations of the medical condition while symptoms are the subjective experience of the medical condition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Stage
member.summary: The stage of the condition, if applicable.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.Subtype
member.summary: A more specific type of the condition, where applicable, for example 'Type 1 Diabetes', 'Type 2 Diabetes', or 'Gestational Diabetes' for Diabetes.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalCondition.TypicalTest
member.summary: A medical test typically performed given this condition.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalConditionStage
member.summary: A stage of a medical condition, such as 'Stage IIIa'.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalConditionStage.StageAsNumber
member.summary: The stage represented as a number, e.g. 3.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalConditionStage.SubStageSuffix
member.summary: The substage, e.g. 'a' for Stage IIIa.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalContraindication
member.summary: A condition or factor that serves as a reason to withhold a certain medical therapy. Contraindications can be absolute (there are no reasonable circumstances for undertaking a course of action) or relative (the patient is at higher risk of complications, but that these risks may be outweighed by other considerations or mitigated by other measures).

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice
member.summary: Any object used in a medical capacity, such as to diagnose or treat a patient.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.AdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or is otherwise life-threatening or requires immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriouseAdverseOutcome instead.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.Contraindication
member.summary: A contraindication for this therapy.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.Indication
member.summary: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. These can be distinguished by using the ApprovedIndication subtype of MedicalIndication.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.PostOp
member.summary: A description of the postoperative procedures, care, and/or followups for this device.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.PreOp
member.summary: A description of the workup, testing, and other preparations required before implanting this device.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.Procedure
member.summary: A description of the procedure involved in setting up, using, and/or installing the device.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.Purpose
member.summary: A goal towards an action is taken. Can be concrete or abstract.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevice.SeriousAdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalDevicePurpose
member.summary: Categories of medical devices, organized by the purpose or intended use of the device.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEntity
member.summary: The most generic type of entity related to health and the practice of medicine.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEntity.Code
member.summary: A medical code for the entity, taken from a controlled vocabulary or ontology such as ICD-9, DiseasesDB, MeSH, SNOMED-CT, RxNorm, etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEntity.Guideline
member.summary: A medical guideline related to this entity.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEntity.MedicineSystem
member.summary: The system of medicine that includes this MedicalEntity, for example 'evidence-based', 'homeopathic', 'chiropractic', etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEntity.RecognizingAuthority
member.summary: If applicable, the organization that officially recognizes this entity as part of its endorsed system of medicine.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEntity.RelevantSpecialty
member.summary: If applicable, a medical specialty in which this entity is relevant.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEntity.Study
member.summary: A medical study or trial related to this entity.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEnumeration
member.summary: Enumerations related to health and the practice of medicine.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalEvidenceLevel
member.summary: Level of evidence for a medical guideline. Enumerated type.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuideline
member.summary: Any recommendation made by a standard society (e.g. ACC/AHA) or consensus statement that denotes how to diagnose and treat a particular condition. Note: this type should be used to tag the actual guideline recommendation; if the guideline recommendation occurs in a larger scholarly article, use MedicalScholarlyArticle to tag the overall article, not this type. Note also: the organization making the recommendation should be captured in the recognizingAuthority base property of MedicalEntity.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuideline.EvidenceLevel
member.summary: Strength of evidence of the data used to formulate the guideline (enumerated).

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuideline.EvidenceOrigin
member.summary: Source of the data used to formulate the guidance, e.g. RCT, consensus opinion, etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuideline.GuidelineDate
member.summary: Date on which this guideline's recommendation was made.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuideline.GuidelineSubject
member.summary: The medical conditions, treatments, etc. that are the subject of the guideline.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuidelineContraindication
member.summary: A guideline contraindication that designates a process as harmful and where quality of the data supporting the contraindication is sound.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuidelineRecommendation
member.summary: A guideline recommendation that is regarded as efficacious and where quality of the data supporting the recommendation is sound.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.RecommendationStrength
member.summary: Strength of the guideline's recommendation (e.g. 'class I').

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalImagingTechnique
member.summary: Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes. Enumerated type.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalIndication
member.summary: A condition or factor that indicates use of a medical therapy, including signs, symptoms, risk factors, anatomical states, etc.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalIntangible
member.summary: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things in the medical space.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalObservationalStudy
member.summary: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalObservationalStudy.StudyDesign
member.summary: Specifics about the observational study design (enumerated).

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalObservationalStudyDesign
member.summary: Design models for observational medical studies. Enumerated type.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalOrganization
member.summary: A medical organization, such as a doctor's office or clinic.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalProcedure
member.summary: A process of care used in either a diagnostic, therapeutic, or palliative capacity that relies on invasive (surgical), non-invasive, or percutaneous techniques.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalProcedure.Followup
member.summary: Typical or recommended followup care after the procedure is performed.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalProcedure.HowPerformed
member.summary: How the procedure is performed.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalProcedure.Preparation
member.summary: Typical preparation that a patient must undergo before having the procedure performed.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalProcedure.ProcedureType
member.summary: The type of procedure, for example Surgical, Noninvasive, or Percutaneous.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalProcedureType
member.summary: An enumeration that describes different types of medical procedures.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalResearcher
member.summary: Medical researchers.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskCalculator
member.summary: A complex mathematical calculation requiring an online calculator, used to assess prognosis. Note: use the url property of Thing to record any URLs for online calculators.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskEstimator
member.summary: Any rule set or interactive tool for estimating the risk of developing a complication or condition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskEstimator.EstimatesRiskOf
member.summary: The condition, complication, or symptom whose risk is being estimated.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskEstimator.IncludedRiskFactor
member.summary: A modifiable or non-modifiable risk factor included in the calculation, e.g. age, coexisting condition.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskFactor
member.summary: A risk factor is anything that increases a person's likelihood of developing or contracting a disease, medical condition, or complication.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskFactor.IncreasesRiskOf
member.summary: The condition, complication, etc. influenced by this factor.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskScore
member.summary: A simple system that adds up the number of risk factors to yield a score that is associated with prognosis, e.g. CHAD score, TIMI risk score.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalRiskScore.Algorithm
member.summary: The algorithm or rules to follow to compute the score.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalScholarlyArticle
member.summary: A scholarly article in the medical domain.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalScholarlyArticle.PublicationType
member.summary: The type of the medical article, taken from the US NLM MeSH publication type catalog.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSign
member.summary: Any physical manifestation of a person's medical condition discoverable by objective diagnostic tests or physical examination.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSign.IdentifyingExam
member.summary: A physical examination that can identify this sign.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSign.IdentifyingTest
member.summary: A diagnostic test that can identify this sign.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSignOrSymptom
member.summary: Any indication of the existence of a medical condition or disease.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSignOrSymptom.Cause
member.summary: An underlying cause. More specifically, one of the causative agent(s) that are most directly responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in the occurrence.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSignOrSymptom.PossibleTreatment
member.summary: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSpecialty
member.summary: Any specific branch of medical science or practice. Medical specialities include clinical specialties that pertain to particular organ systems and their respective disease states, as well as allied health specialties. Enumerated type.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy
member.summary: A medical study is an umbrella type covering all kinds of research studies relating to human medicine or health, including observational studies and interventional trials and registries, randomized, controlled or not. When the specific type of study is known, use one of the extensions of this type, such as MedicalTrial or MedicalObservationalStudy. Also, note that this type should be used to mark up data that describes the study itself; to tag an article that publishes the results of a study, use MedicalScholarlyArticle. Note: use the code property of MedicalEntity to store study IDs, e.g. clinicaltrials.gov ID.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy.Outcome
member.summary: Expected or actual outcomes of the study.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy.Population
member.summary: Any characteristics of the population used in the study, e.g. 'males under 65'.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy.Sponsor
member.summary: Sponsor of the study.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy.Status
member.summary: The status of the study (enumerated).

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy.StudyLocation
member.summary: The location in which the study is taking/took place.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudy.StudySubject
member.summary: A subject of the study, i.e. one of the medical conditions, therapies, devices, drugs, etc. investigated by the study.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalStudyStatus
member.summary: The status of a medical study. Enumerated type.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalSymptom
member.summary: Any indication of the existence of a medical condition or disease that is apparent to the patient.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTest
member.summary: Any medical test, typically performed for diagnostic purposes.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTest.AffectedBy
member.summary: Drugs that affect the test's results.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTest.NormalRange
member.summary: Range of acceptable values for a typical patient, when applicable.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTest.SignDetected
member.summary: A sign detected by the test.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTest.UsedToDiagnose
member.summary: A condition the test is used to diagnose.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTest.UsesDevice
member.summary: Device used to perform the test.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTestPanel
member.summary: Any collection of tests commonly ordered together.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTestPanel.SubTest
member.summary: A component test of the panel.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy
member.summary: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.AdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible complication and/or side effect of this therapy. If it is known that an adverse outcome is serious (resulting in death, disability, or permanent damage; requiring hospitalization; or is otherwise life-threatening or requires immediate medical attention), tag it as a seriouseAdverseOutcome instead.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.Contraindication
member.summary: A contraindication for this therapy.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.DuplicateTherapy
member.summary: A therapy that duplicates or overlaps this one.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.Indication
member.summary: A factor that indicates use of this therapy for treatment and/or prevention of a condition, symptom, etc. For therapies such as drugs, indications can include both officially-approved indications as well as off-label uses. These can be distinguished by using the ApprovedIndication subtype of MedicalIndication.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTherapy.SeriousAdverseOutcome
member.summary: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTrial
member.summary: A medical trial is a type of medical study that uses scientific process used to compare the safety and efficacy of medical therapies or medical procedures. In general, medical trials are controlled and subjects are allocated at random to the different treatment and/or control groups.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTrial.Phase
member.summary: The phase of the trial.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTrial.TrialDesign
member.summary: Specifics about the trial design (enumerated).

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalTrialDesign
member.summary: Design models for medical trials. Enumerated type.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalWebPage
member.summary: A web page that provides medical information.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicalWebPage.Aspect
member.summary: An aspect of medical practice that is considered on the page, such as 'diagnosis', 'treatment', 'causes', 'prognosis', 'etiology', 'epidemiology', etc.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MedicineSystem
member.summary: Systems of medical practice.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MensClothingStore
member.summary: A men's clothing store.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MiddleSchool
member.summary: A middle school (typically for children aged around 11-14, although this varies somewhat).

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Midwifery
member.summary: Midwifery.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MixtapeAlbum
member.summary: MixtapeAlbum.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MobileApplication
member.summary: A software application designed specifically to work well on a mobile device such as a telephone.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MobileApplication.CarrierRequirements
member.summary: Specifies specific carrier(s) requirements for the application (e.g. an application may only work on a specific carrier network).

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MobilePhoneStore
member.summary: A store that sells mobile phones and related accessories.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Mosque
member.summary: A mosque.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Motel
member.summary: A motel.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MotorcycleDealer
member.summary: A motorcycle dealer.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MotorcycleRepair
member.summary: A motorcycle repair shop.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Mountain
member.summary: A mountain, like Mount Whitney or Mount Everest.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MoveAction
member.summary: The act of an agent relocating to a place.Related actions:TransferAction: Unlike TransferAction, the subject of the move is a living Person or Organization rather than an inanimate object.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MoveAction.FromLocation
member.summary: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MoveAction.ToLocation
member.summary: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Movie
member.summary: A movie.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Movie.Actor
member.summary: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip. Supersedes actors.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Movie.Director
member.summary: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip. Supersedes directors.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Movie.Duration
member.summary: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in ISO 8601 date format.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Movie.MusicBy
member.summary: The composer of the soundtrack.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Movie.ProductionCompany
member.summary: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Movie.Trailer
member.summary: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovieRentalStore
member.summary: A movie rental store.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovieSeries
member.summary: A series of movies. Included movies can be indicated with the hasPart property.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovieSeries.Director
member.summary: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip. Supersedes directors.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovieSeries.MusicBy
member.summary: The composer of the soundtrack.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovieSeries.ProductionCompany
member.summary: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovieSeries.Trailer
member.summary: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovieTheater
member.summary: A movie theater.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MovingCompany
member.summary: A moving company.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MRI
member.summary: Magnetic resonance imaging.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MulticellularParasite
member.summary: Multicellular parasite that causes an infection.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MultiCenterTrial
member.summary: A trial that takes place at multiple centers.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MultiPlayer
member.summary: Play mode: MultiPlayer. Requiring or allowing multiple human players to play simultaneously.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Muscle
member.summary: A muscle is an anatomical structure consisting of a contractile form of tissue that animals use to effect movement.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Muscle.Antagonist
member.summary: The muscle whose action counteracts the specified muscle.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Muscle.BloodSupply
member.summary: The blood vessel that carries blood from the heart to the muscle.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Muscle.Insertion
member.summary: The place of attachment of a muscle, or what the muscle moves.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Muscle.MuscleAction
member.summary: The movement the muscle generates. Supersedes action.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Muscle.Nerve
member.summary: The underlying innervation associated with the muscle.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Muscle.Origin
member.summary: The place or point where a muscle arises.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Musculoskeletal
member.summary: A specific branch of medical science that pertains to diagnosis and treatment of disorders of muscles, ligaments and skeletal system.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusculoskeletalExam
member.summary: Musculoskeletal.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.Museum
member.summary: A museum.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicAlbum
member.summary: A collection of music tracks.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicAlbum.AlbumProductionType
member.summary: Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicAlbum.AlbumRelease
member.summary: A release of this album. Inverse property: releaseOf.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicAlbum.AlbumReleaseType
member.summary: The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicAlbum.ByArtist
member.summary: The artist that performed this album or recording.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicAlbumProductionType
member.summary: Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicAlbumReleaseType
member.summary: The kind of release which this album is: single, EP or album.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition
member.summary: A musical composition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.Composer
member.summary: The person or organization who wrote the composition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.FirstPerformance
member.summary: The date and place the work was first performed.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.IncludedComposition
member.summary: Smaller compositions included in this work (e.g. a movement in a symphony).

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.IswcCode
member.summary: The International Standard Musical Work Code for the composition.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.Lyricist

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.MusicArrangement

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.MusicCompositionForm
member.summary: The type of composition (e.g. overture, sonata, symphony, etc.).

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.MusicalKey
member.summary: The key, mode, or scale this composition uses.

member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicComposition.RecordedAs
member.summary: An audio recording of the work. Inverse property: recordingOf.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicEvent
member.summary: Event type: Music event.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.MusicGroup
member.summary: A musical group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a choir. Can also be a solo musician.

Usage guidelines:Use the priceCurrency property (with ISO 4217 codes e.g. "USD") instead of including ambiguous symbols such as '$' in the value. Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator. member.name: P:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.PriceSpecification.Price
member.summary: The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes. Usage guidelines:Use the priceCurrency property (with ISO 4217 codes e.g. "USD") instead of including ambiguous symbols such as '$' in the value. Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator. Note that both RDFa and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting. Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

member.name: T:Bam.Net.Schema.Org.SuperficialAnatomy
member.summary: Anatomical features that can be observed by sight (without dissection), including the form and proportions of the human body as well as surface landmarks that correspond to deeper subcutaneous structures. Superficial anatomy plays an important role in sports medicine, phlebotomy, and other medical specialties as underlying anatomical structures can be identified through surface palpation. For example, during back surgery, superficial anatomy can be used to palpate and count vertebrae to find the site of incision. Or in phlebotomy, superficial anatomy can be used to locate an underlying vein; for example, the median cubital vein can be located by palpating the borders of the cubital fossa (such as the epicondyles of the humerus) and then looking for the superficial signs of the vein, such as size, prominence, ability to refill after depression, and feel of surrounding tissue support. As another example, in a subluxation (dislocation) of the glenohumeral joint, the bony structure becomes pronounced with the deltoid muscle failing to cover the glenohumeral joint allowing the edges of the scapula to be superficially visible. Here, the superficial anatomy is the visible edges of the scapula, implying the underlying dislocation of the joint (the related anatomical structure).

Usage guidelines:Use the priceCurrency property (with ISO 4217 codes e.g. "USD") instead of including ambiguous symbols such as '$' in the value. Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
